Weft — Dual Licensing
=====================

This repository is dual-licensed, deliberately, to serve two different goals
per the design document's §26.2 (governance, plurality, and the designed-in
right to fork):

  1. The **protocol engine** and its test harness are permissively licensed
     so any other client — including forks with different UI decisions or
     different runtime targets — may embed them without inheriting a
     copyleft obligation. This makes Weft compatible with DD §11.5's
     client-plurality/substitutability defense.

  2. The **reference client** (PWA and headless porch node) is copyleft so
     that a forked or hosted variant must publish its source. This is the
     block against DD §11.5's poison-the-well risk: a closed,
     data-harvesting client wearing Weft's name.

If you disagree with either choice, DD §26.2's separable-trademark posture
applies: fork the code, publish under your license, ship under your name.
The protocol is the product; the name is severable from it.


License by path
---------------

  weft/packages/core/**                Apache-2.0    (see LICENSE-APACHE-2.0)
  weft/packages/sim/**                 Apache-2.0    (see LICENSE-APACHE-2.0)
  weft/packages/pwa/**                 AGPL-3.0     (see LICENSE-AGPL-3.0)
  weft/packages/porch/**               AGPL-3.0     (see LICENSE-AGPL-3.0)

  All Markdown documents at repository root
  and under weft/docs/**               Apache-2.0    (see LICENSE-APACHE-2.0)

Files not listed inherit Apache-2.0 (the more permissive of the two — a
conservative default for anything that later moves between packages).


SPDX identifiers
----------------

Every package.json in this repository declares its license via the SPDX
"license" field. If the path table above and a package.json disagree, the
package.json wins for that package (it is closer to the code); please open
an issue so the mismatch can be corrected.


Full license texts
------------------

The complete texts of both licenses are in this repository:

  LICENSE-APACHE-2.0   Apache License, Version 2.0, January 2004
  LICENSE-AGPL-3.0     GNU Affero General Public License, Version 3, 19 Nov 2007

Both files are the canonical texts as published by their respective
stewards (the Apache Software Foundation and the Free Software Foundation).
They have not been modified.


